The railway system gracing [Vietnam](/Vietnam) is, as one might expect, entirely under the purview of the state-owned [Vietnam Railways](/Vietnam_Railways) ([Vietnamese](/Vietnamese_language): Đường sắt Việt Nam ), a venerable institution that has, by necessity, adapted to rather than mastered the nation's challenging geography and tumultuous history. At its heart, or perhaps its spine, lies the primary artery: the [single track](/Single_track_(rail)) [North-South Railway](/North%E2%80%93South_Railway_(Vietnam)). This crucial line, stretching with a weary determination between the historic capital of [Hanoi](/Hanoi) in the north and the bustling metropolis of [Ho Chi Minh City](/Ho_Chi_Minh_City) in the south, claims a substantial 1,726 kilometres (1,072&#160;mi) of the network’s modest total length, which barely scrapes 2,600 kilometres (1,600&#160;mi).

The national railway infrastructure, a testament to historical circumstance more than cohesive planning, predominantly employs the narrower [metre gauge](/Metre_gauge). However, for those who appreciate logistical quirks, the northern reaches of the country offer a fascinating, if sometimes inconvenient, blend of [standard gauge](/Standard_gauge) and [mixed gauge](/Mixed_gauge) lines. This varied track width is a legacy of differing colonial and wartime influences, rather than a deliberate strategic choice, and frequently necessitates the cumbersome process of [gauge conversion](/Gauge_conversion) or transshipment at junctions.

